The Games of the XVIII Olympiad, commonly known as the [1964 Summer Olympics](/1964_Summer_Olympics) and officially as the Games of the XVIII Olympiad, were a grand spectacle of international [multi-sport](/Multi-sport_event) competition held in [Tokyo](/Tokyo), [Japan](/Japan). The event spanned from October 10th to October 24th, 1964, bringing together athletes from across the globe. It's worth noting that Tokyo had previously been awarded the honor of hosting the [1940 Summer Olympics](/1940_Summer_Olympics), a distinction that was ultimately rescinded due to Japan's escalating involvement in the [Second Sino-Japanese War](/Second_Sino-Japanese_War), and later cancelled altogether due to the outbreak of [World War II](/World_War_II). The 1964 Games marked Tokyo's inaugural experience as an Olympic host city. In a rather poignant twist of fate, these Games were the last to allow spectators in person, a privilege that would be denied to the [2020 Summer Olympics](/2020_Summer_Olympics) in the same city, due to the global [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic). The decision to award Tokyo the hosting rights was made on May 26, 1959, during the 55th [IOC Session](/IOC_Session) held in West Germany.

These particular Olympic Games held immense significance as they were the first to be staged on the continent of [Asia](/Asia). Furthermore, they marked a pivotal moment in the Olympic movement's stance against discrimination, as [South Africa was excluded](/Apartheid-era_South_Africa_and_the_Olympics) from participation due to its deeply entrenched policy of [apartheid](/Apartheid) in sports. While South Africa had previously sent racially segregated teams, the [International Olympic Committee](/International_Olympic_Committee) demanded a unified, multi-racial delegation for the 1964 Games. South Africa's refusal to comply led to their ban. Interestingly, the nation was permitted to compete in the [1964 Summer Paralympics](/1964_Summer_Paralympics), also hosted in Tokyo, marking their debut in the Paralympic Games.

The 1964 Tokyo Olympics also heralded a new era in sports broadcasting. For the first time, these Games were telecast internationally without the necessity of shipping recorded tapes across continents, a practice that had been standard for the [1960 Summer Olympics](/1960_Summer_Olympics) four years prior. Utilizing the groundbreaking [Syncom 3](/Syncom) satellite, the first [geostationary](/Geostationary_orbit) communication satellite, live broadcasts were transmitted to the United States, and subsequently relayed to Europe via [Relay 1](/Relay_1). While these broadcasts were primarily in black and white, the Games also featured experimental color telecasts. Popular Japanese sports like sumo wrestling and judo were showcased using [Toshiba](/Toshiba)'s new color transmission technology, though these were for domestic viewing only. The enduring legacy of these Games was further cemented by the critically acclaimed 1965 documentary film [Tokyo Olympiad](/Tokyo_Olympiad), masterfully directed by [Kon Ichikawa](/Kon_Ichikawa).

The scheduling of the Games in mid-October was a deliberate choice to circumvent the oppressive heat and humidity of Tokyo's midsummer and the disruptive [typhoon](/Typhoon) season that typically occurred in September. This contrasted with the [Rome](/Rome) Games of [1960](/1960_Summer_Olympics), which experienced considerable heat, and the subsequent [1968 Summer Olympics](/1968_Summer_Olympics) in [Mexico City](/Mexico_City), which also commenced in October. The 1964 Olympics also held the distinction of being the final Summer Games to utilize the traditional cinder track for athletics events; subsequent Games would feature the smoother, all-weather synthetic tracks. In terms of athletic prowess, the United States emerged as the leader in the gold medal count, while the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) secured the highest number of overall medals.

Years later, in 2021, Tokyo once again found itself in the Olympic spotlight, hosting the [2020 Summer Olympics](/2020_Summer_Olympics). This made Tokyo the first city in Asia to host the Summer Games on two separate occasions. Japan's experience with hosting the Olympic Games extends to the Winter edition as well, with [Sapporo](/Sapporo) hosting in [1972](/1972_Winter_Olympics) and [Nagano](/Nagano_(city)) in [1998](/1998_Winter_Olympics).

### Host City Selection

The selection process for the 1964 Summer Olympics host city culminated on May 26, 1959, at the 55th [IOC Session](/IOC_Session) held in Munich, [West Germany](/West_Germany). Tokyo emerged victorious, securing the rights over competing bids from Detroit, Brussels, and Vienna. [Toronto](/Toronto), which had previously made an unsuccessful bid for the 1960 Games, once again put forth its candidacy but did not advance to the final selection round.

The results of the [1964 Summer Olympics bidding](/Bids_for_the_1964_Summer_Olympics) process were as follows:

| City     | Country       | Round 1 |
| :------- | :------------ | :------ |
| Tokyo    | [Japan](/Japan)       | 34      |
| Detroit  | [United States](/United_States) | 10      |
| Vienna   | [Austria](/Austria)     | 9       |
| Brussels | [Belgium](/Belgium)     | 5       |

### Highlights

The 1964 Tokyo Olympics were replete with memorable moments and significant achievements:

*   The iconic lighting of the [Olympic flame](/Olympic_flame) was performed by [Yoshinori Sakai](/Yoshinori_Sakai). His selection was deeply symbolic, as he was born in [Hiroshima](/Hiroshima) on August 6, 1945, the very day the city endured the atomic bombing. His role embodied Japan's remarkable postwar recovery and its commitment to peace.
*   The vibrant sounds of [Kumi-daiko](/Kumi-daiko) were introduced to a global audience during the Festival of Arts presentation, offering a glimpse into traditional Japanese drumming.
*   [Judo](/Judo) and [volleyball](/Volleyball), both deeply ingrained in Japanese culture, made their official Olympic debuts. While Japan celebrated victories in judo, the Dutch judoka [Anton Geesink](/Anton_Geesink) achieved a significant triumph by winning the Open category, defeating Japan's [Akio Kaminaga](/Akio_Kaminaga) on home soil. The [Japanese women's volleyball team](/Japan_women%27s_national_volleyball_team) also captured the gold medal, with their final match drawing massive viewership.
*   The [women's pentathlon](/Women%27s_pentathlon), a demanding event comprising [shot put](/Shot_put), [high jump](/High_jump), [hurdling](/Hurdling), [sprint](/Sprint_(running)), and [long jump](/Long_jump), was added to the athletics program.
*   Wrestler [Osamu Watanabe](/Osamu_Watanabe) of Japan concluded his illustrious career with a gold medal in freestyle wrestling, an achievement made more remarkable by the fact that he surrendered no points throughout the competition. He retired undefeated, holding the unique distinction of being the only undefeated Olympic champion at that time, with a record of 189 wins and 0 losses.
*   Soviet gymnast [Larisa Latynina](/Larisa_Latynina) continued to add to her impressive medal collection, securing two gold, one silver, and two bronze medals. Her record of 18 Olympic medals (nine gold, five silver, four bronze) stood as a benchmark until it was surpassed by [Michael Phelps](/Michael_Phelps) in [2012](/2012_Summer_Olympics).
*   [Věra Čáslavská](/V%C4%9Bra_%C4%8C%C3%A1slavsk%C3%A1) of [Czechoslovakia](/Czechoslovakia) claimed three gold medals, including the coveted individual all-around title, establishing herself as a dominant force in gymnastics.
*   Australian swimmer [Dawn Fraser](/Dawn_Fraser) achieved a remarkable feat by winning the 100m freestyle event for the third consecutive Olympics. This same accomplishment was mirrored by Soviet rower [Vyacheslav Ivanov](/Vyacheslav_Ivanov_(rower)) in the single scull event.
*   American swimmer [Don Schollander](/Don_Schollander) showcased his exceptional talent by winning four gold medals in swimming events.
*   [Abebe Bikila](/Abebe_Bikila) of [Ethiopia](/Ethiopia) etched his name in history by becoming the first athlete to win the Olympic [marathon](/Marathon_(sport)) twice.
*   The prodigious 15-year-old swimmer [Sharon Stouder](/Sharon_Stouder) from the United States garnered four medals, three of which were gold.
*   New Zealand's [Peter Snell](/Peter_Snell) joined an elite group of athletes by winning gold medals in both the 800m and 1500m races, a feat previously achieved only by Albert Hill and Edwin Flack.
*   In a stunning upset, [Billy Mills](/Billy_Mills), an American runner considered an underdog, became the first and only Native American to win the gold medal in the men's 10,000m race.
*   [Bob Hayes](/Bob_Hayes) of the United States claimed the 100-meter title with a time of 10.06 seconds, equalling the world record, and also anchored the 4×100m relay team to a new world record with his blistering leg.
*   Future [heavyweight boxing champion](/Heavyweight_champion) of the world, [Joe Frazier](/Joe_Frazier), secured a gold medal in the heavyweight division, competing with a broken thumb.
*   These Games marked the last occasion where a [cinder](/Cinder_track) running track was used for athletic competitions. Simultaneously, they were the first Olympics to incorporate [fiberglass](/Fiberglass) poles in the [pole vault](/Pole_vault) event.
*   On the day of the closing ceremony, [Zambia](/Zambia) declared its independence, making it the first country to participate in an Olympic Games under one name and depart under another. The Zambian team proudly marched with a placard bearing their new nation's name during the closing ceremony, a unique occurrence.
*   The inauguration of Japan's revolutionary high-speed rail system, the [Tōkaidō Shinkansen](/T%C5%8Dkaid%C5%8D_Shinkansen), often referred to as the "bullet train," was strategically timed to coincide with the Olympic Games. The first scheduled service commenced on October 1st, 1964, connecting [Tokyo Station](/Tokyo_Station) with [Shin-Ōsaka Station](/Shin-%C5%8Csaka_Station) and significantly reducing travel time between major metropolitan areas.
*   [Ranatunge Karunananda](/Ranatunge_Karunananda), representing [Ceylon](/Ceylon_at_the_1964_Summer_Olympics) in the men's [10,000 meters](/10,000_meters), became a symbol of perseverance. He continued to run alone even after all other competitors had finished, initially met with jeers but ultimately earning a standing ovation. His remarkable display of sportsmanship earned him a place in Japanese school textbooks, under the title 'Uniform Number 67', 'Bottom Ranked Hero'.

