### Participating National Olympic Committees

A remarkable ninety-four nations sent athletes to compete in the 1964 Games. Sixteen nations made their Olympic debut in Tokyo: [Algeria](/Algeria), [Cameroon](/Cameroon), [Chad](/Chad), [Republic of the Congo](/Republic_of_Congo), [Côte d'Ivoire](/C%C3%B4te_d%27Ivoire) (then known as Ivory Coast), [Dominican Republic](/Dominican_Republic), [Libya](/Kingdom_of_Libya) (though its sole athlete withdrew before competition), [Madagascar](/Madagascar), [Malaysia](/Malaysia), [Mali](/Mali), [Mongolia](/Mongolian_People%27s_Republic), [Nepal](/Kingdom_of_Nepal), [Niger](/Niger), [Northern Rhodesia](/Northern_Rhodesia), [Senegal](/Senegal), and [Tanzania](/Tanzania) (as Tanganyika). Malaysia had previously competed under the name [Malaya](/Federation_of_Malaya).

[Northern Rhodesia](/Northern_Rhodesia) achieved its independence as [Zambia](/Zambia) on the same day as the closing ceremony, marking a significant historical moment. Athletes from [Southern Rhodesia](/Southern_Rhodesia) competed under the name [Rhodesia](/Rhodesia_(name)), this being their third and final appearance at the Summer Olympics. The nation of [Zimbabwe](/Zimbabwe_at_the_Olympics) would later make its debut at the [1980 Summer Olympics](/1980_Summer_Olympics).

Athletes from [East Germany](/East_Germany) and [West Germany](/West_Germany) competed as a unified team, known as the [United Team of Germany](/United_Team_of_Germany), a continuation of the practice from the 1956 and 1960 Games. However, from the [1968 Winter Olympics](/1968_Winter_Olympics) onwards, these nations began fielding separate teams.

[Indonesia](/Indonesia) was initially banned from the 1964 Olympics due to its refusal to grant visas to athletes from [Israel](/Israel) and [Taiwan](/Taiwan) for the [1962 Asian Games](/1962_Asian_Games). This ban, decided upon in Lausanne on February 7, 1963, was eventually lifted on June 26, 1964, following a shift in the [Government of Indonesia](/Government_of_Indonesia)'s stance regarding the Tokyo Games.

